post_text:
**HS FB at home tonight w/Flinthills.
**We will be honoring our senior football and volleyball players, band members, and cheerleaders and their parents. Senior Night activities are planned for 6:40; kickoff is at 7:00.
**This is an SCBL activity, so SCBL policies will be followed for an outdoor activity. In order to social distance at the gate, we will use the big gate at the south end of the field for the main entrance. The smaller gate between the two sets of bleachers on the home side will be shut until after halftime. The bridge gate and visitor gate on the east side will be open.
**Admission will be charged $5 for adults and $4 for students K-12. All 9-12 grade students that wear black and sit and cheer in the student section will receive free admission.
**Come on out tonight and support our fall activity seniors and our football team at the home season opener!

post_text:
SPARK Meeting Thursday, September 10, 2020, @ Sedan High School Auditorium. Forms for the grants can be found on the following link:

https://www.chautauquacountyks.com/caresspark

We have posted the following documents -- Chautauqua County SPARK Funds Grant Eligibility Requirements, Chautauqua County SPARK Funds Grant Application, and the sample Grant Funds Agreement successful applicants must sign in order to receive grant funds. Federal or state guidance may affect this process. We will post any changes, if any, as soon as we are so advised by the state or federal government or as directed by Mr. Scot Loyd, the County's consultant.

As we go through this process we thank you for your understanding as the situation is very fluid. We continue to be grateful to Mr. Loyd for his help and look forward to his town hall meeting on September 10, 2020, at 5:30 P.M. The meeting will be held at the Sedan High School auditorium.

After-school program enrolling now!

The After School Program is for students K-5th grade and is focused on academic support, mentoring, student development, art and recreation. Students will receive a snack, and then head to their breakout groups for homework help, reading/math enrichment, and hands-on STEM and art activities. This is a great opportunity for students to actively engage in learning and creating while having fun this 2020-2021 school year.

Sign up today!

post_text: Preparing for social distancing. Can’t wait to have our students back!
text: Preparing for social distancing. Can’t wait to have our students back!

post_text:
COVID Procedure Updates:
We will highly encourage all students to wear masks.
Surfaces will be cleaned between class periods.
Bathrooms will be cleaned and highly touched surfaces will be cleaned throughout the day. (Extra custodial staff has been hired)
Additional lunch periods have been added to increase social distancing.
Students will have scheduled handwashing and sanitizing times.
Temperatures checked before entering the building.
Every classroom has a wall-mounted hand sanitizer.
School Nurse has an isolation room for students as needed.
Masks have been purchased for every student.
Bottle fillers to fill water bottles/closed water fountains.

We care about the safety and health of all our students. We are in contact with CQ County Health, City Hosptial, and County Commissioners as we work through these trying times.

post_text:
Chautauqua County passed the following Resolutions 2020-09 and 2020-10 on August 10, 2020, exempting Chautauqua County from EO 20-59 the Governor's Order requiring masks.

USD 286 will follow Chautauqua County Resolutions 2020-09 & 2020-10, guidelines from KSDE Navigating Change, and the Chautauqua County Health Department.

USD 286 will not require students to wear masks, but we will highly recommend students to wear masks, especially in hallways (passing periods), on buses, and when you cannot social distance.

shared_text:
Governor Laura Kelly
July 15 at 4:10 PM ·

Today, following the news of the worst COVID-19 spike in Kansas, I announced that I will issue an executive order next Monday to delay opening schools until after the Labor Day holiday. The order will also make commonsense public health tools like masks, hygiene protocols, and temperatures checks mandatory for every school when they reopen.

Every action I have taken throughout this pandemic has been in done with three things in mind: Keeping Kansans healthy, keeping our state open for business and getting our kids back to school.

Real leaders aren’t afraid to confront crises head on, they don’t sit back silently and wait for the situation to get worse. That’s what I have done and will continue to do, regardless of the political consequences.

GREAT NEWS! We have some open spots for our summer boost program! Please click the link below to enroll!!

Enroll now for the Wild Wild West summer program for students K-5th grade. Students will meet July 6th-31st, Monday - Friday from 8:00am-12:20pm with breakfast, lunch and bus transportation provided.

Students will be split in grade-level groups to complete math and reading enrichment while also engaging in hands-on STEM projects.

Additionally, students will spend time in P.E., computer apps, and art. We look forward to this summer to help your child learn, grow, and develop important skills to support them in the next academic year.

To register for the elementary program, click here: Elementary Summer Boost https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1ZoM2-iHY6MvV3nbsYr1cvQRWsczfr8CsKh9C5eT06qo/viewform?edit_requested=true

Information is also available on our school webpage at www.usd286.org

Sedan Elementary would like to introduce our new 3rd grade teacher for the 2020-2021 school year, Ms. Kylie Hurt.

I am from Howard Kansas and will be graduating from Kansas State University in May 2020. My favorite color is PURPLE, and my favorite animal is a cow! I love being outdoors planting flowers, fishing, or playing sports. My favorite quote is “believe that you can, and you are halfway there,” by Theodore Roosevelt. Math is my favorite subject and fall is my favorite season. I am indescribably excited to teach 3rd grade at Sedan Elementary School. I am most excited to be a part of such a supportive and proud atmosphere.

post_text: Attention 6-11th graders and parents: There are several Zooms that overlap for certain students. Sorry, but we couldn't find a way to prevent some overlapping. All teachers are recording their live zooms and posting them to Google Classroom. If you have live Zooms that overlap, make sure your teachers know that they are at the same time for you. Students let teachers know that on "this" day you will be with the live Zoom with "this" class and on "this" day you will be on the live Zoom with "this" class. If a teacher absolutely needs you on the live version one day, they will let you know. Students/Parents, if you have any questions, call the school at 620-725-3186 or email Mrs. Williams - williamsc@usd286.org or Mrs. Hill - hillk@usd286.org.

post_text: SCHOLARSHIP UPDATE! Class of 2020 and Alumni: Several scholarship deadlines are approaching and one deadline has changed. The Russell Family Foundation Scholarship is due April 1. If you are in the top 50% of the Class of 2020, you should apply. If you received this scholarship as a senior and are still attending school, alumni need to reapply. Class of 2020 - The Chautauqua County Farm Bureau Scholarship is also due April 1 and the Coco Sutton Memorial Scholarship is due April 5. There has been a change to the Cude Memorial Scholarship deadline. The deadline for the Class of 2020 AND alumni wanting to apply is now April 15. Absolutely NO late applications will be accepted. If you need more information, have questions or want Mrs. Williams to get your completed application in the mail - please email williamsc@usd286.org or call the school on Monday, 620-725-3186.

post_text:
In a press conference tonight (3/17), Governor Kelly announced that all Kansas schools are "shut down" for the rest of the semester. All schools will be required to submit a Continuous Learning Plan, to teach students. We understand this brings many questions and concerns. USD 286 leaders will meet tonight with our Board of Education tonight to discuss next steps. Please check back for more information.

Schools are closed but learning will still be taking place. More details to come.

shared_text:
Kansas State Department of Education
March 15 at 4:32 PM ·

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation

USD 286 will be closed the Week of March 16-20th. This is information we have received from the KS Education Commissioner. This will include all spring sport practices and other extracurricular activities. Check back for more information.

As of Sunday, March 15, Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson strongly recommends that those schools currently coming off of spring break, suspend operations for the week March 16-20. All schools scheduled for spring break the week of March 16-20 will continue as planned. For schools who have spring break later in time, Commissioner Watson is strongly recommending they also close schools for the period of March 16-20.

Closing all schools during this same period of time provides Kansas officials the time needed to finalize a comprehensive plan for how to address COVID-19.

It is critical that we all follow a coordinated response to this situation.

post_text:
Music Students and parents-

I know word has started to spread about Regional Music competitions. I was going to wait until Monday to announce it, however with word out I should update you now.

Regional Music competitions have been cancelled. However as of right now the state music competitions are still on. I am waiting on word from KSHSAA as to how many students I will be allowed to enter into state and we will hold our own competition at school. I will invite someone to come judge so it can be as fair as possible. If we receive any other changes, I will update you in class Monday. If you have more questions we will discuss it on Monday in class. Keep working hard on your solos and ensemble music. We don't want to let down on our hard work. You will get to perform them at some point I promise that!

post_text: Sub-state basketball begins at Sedan on Monday. Monday, March 2nd Sedan girls will face Conway Springs. Game time is 6:00. On Tuesday, March 3rd Sedan boys will face West Elk. Game time is 7:00. Sub-state continues at Sedan on Thursday (2 girls games), Friday (2 boys games), and Saturday (girls championship and boys championship). Games begin at 6:00 each night. Admission will be charged at all games. $7.00 for adults; $5.00 for students K-12. Preschool students will be admitted free of charge. No passes will be accepted. All prices are set by the KSHSAA. Brackets can be found on the KSHSAA website by going to kshsaa.org, Clicking the Athletic tab, Basketball, Regional & Sub-State Assignments. Scroll down to the 2A schools and find the Sedan sub-state. These brackets will be updated after each night's games. For more information or questions, please contact Carolyn Williams at 620-725-3186.
